Normalizing the data

This chunk sets up some helper functions to preprocess the data. It is necessary to normalize the rows (mutation types) of the data or mutations will just cluster by bulk mutation rate instead of subtle differences in rate between populations. There are three ways I’ve written to do this:

  • L1: Set the rates of any mutation \(m\) across the populations so that the total rate is 1. This is the method Segert and I used while developing this analysis.

  • Z: Set the rates of mutation \(m\) to have mean 0 and variance 1 across all populations in the dataset. NOTE: This method does not work if you log-transform the data because you will naturally have negative values in your dataset.

  • fdiff Normalize so that the data for mutation \(m\) is fold difference relative to the mean rate for mutation \(m\) over all pops. This is the reccommended method, which works well with a log transformation.

# helper function that normalizes a vector by z or L1 method
norm <- function(vec, method = c("z", "L1", "fdiff")){
  
  if (method == "L1"){ #normalize so vector sums to 1
    u <- vec/sum(abs(vec))
  }
  else if (method == "z"){ #normalize to mean 0, variance 1
    u <- (vec - mean(vec))/sd(vec)
  }
  else #normalize to fold change compared to mean
    u <- vec/mean(vec)
  
  return(u)
}

# normalizes a whole dataset by calling norm on each row
norm.byrow <- function(mat, m){
  return(t(apply(mat,1,norm, method = m)))
}

The next chunk normalizes by fold difference.

norm.3mer.rates <- norm.byrow(rates.3mer, "fdiff")
norm.5mer.rates <- norm.byrow(rates.5mer, "fdiff")
norm.7mer.rates <- norm.byrow(rates.7mer, "fdiff")

Heatmap generators

This section builds some helper methods that I use to make heatmaps. Each method minimally requires a matrix of rates across populations (data), and a boolean (logunits) for whether a log transform should be used. As a default, logunits is set to true.

  • make.heatmap makes a heatmap of the matrix passed in. A handy workhorse and the helper for the next two functions.

  • subcontext.heatmap makes a heatmap of all of the contexts with the 3mer subcontext “mut” (a string). Requires a reference dataframe (labels).

  • subcontext_list.heatmap makes a heatmaps of all the contexts whose 3mer subcontext falls into a given set, “muts” (a list of 3mer type strings). Requires a reference dataframe (labels).

# makes a heatmap of a matrix
make.heatmap <- function(data, logunits = T){
  complete <- apply(data, 1, function(row) all(row != 0)&all(!is.na(row)))
  data <- data[complete,]
  
  if (logunits == T) {
    data = log2(data)
  }
  heatmap.2(data, trace = 'none',
            col=colorRampPalette(c('blue', "white", 'red'))(n = 1000))
}

# makes a heatmap of all 7mers with a certain 3mer subcontext
subcontext.heatmap <- function(rates, mut, labels, logunits = T){
  data <- subset(rates, labels$X3mer == mut)
  rows <- apply(data, 1, function(row) all(row != 0)&all(!is.na(row)))
  return(make.heatmap(data[rows,], logunits))
}

# makes a heatmap of all kmers with a certain set of 3mer subcontexts
subcontext_list.heatmap <- function(rates, muts, labels, logunits = T){
  data <- subset(rates, labels$X3mer == muts[[1]])
  for (i in 2:length(muts)){
    data <- rbind(data, subset(rates, labels$X3mer == muts[[i]]))
  }
  rows <- apply(data, 1, function(row) all(row != 0)&all(!is.na(row)))
  return(make.heatmap(data[rows,], logunits))
}

Examples

The following code generates some heatmaps from the data that I have found interesting:

1. All 3mers

make.heatmap(norm.3mer.rates)

There are a couple observations to make about this plot:

  1. GGA->A and the rest of the EUR-elevated C->T signal separates out from the other mutations first

  2. The second block of 3mers appears enriched in AFR compared to the rest of the continents. Among them are three *AC->C mutations (AAC->A, GAC->C, and GTA->G) which also appear enriched in JPT and certain other East Asian subpopulations. The other mutations in this block are all CpG transversions. Harris and Pritchard 2017 note that the proportions of these mutation types appear not to agree between 1kg and SGDP, suggesting that this may be an artifact (noteably CCG->A and ACG->G in Figure 2A of that report, and - to a lesser extent - ACG->A in Figure S22A).

  3. The third block of mutations appears enriched in EAS across the continent. It is comprised of two mutations, ATC->A and ACC->A which were noted as highly significant and genome wide consistent in earlier experiments, in addition to a new mutation type, GAC->T, which shares a similar profile with the first two.

Beyond these first three blocks, the remainder of the data is difficult to interpret.

NOTE: heatmapping all 5mers and all 7mers yeilds pretty uninterpretable results (i.e. no clear mutational blocks).

2. 3mers in EAS

Since Harris, Pritchard, and ourselves have noted heterogeneity within 3mer types among East Asian subpopulations, it is reasonable to try the same clustering using just East Asian data to try and indentify signals of heterogeneity within the continental group.

norm.3mer.EAS <- norm.byrow(rates.3mer[,16:20], m = "fdiff")
make.heatmap(norm.3mer.EAS)

This clustering sets apart a group of mutations enriched in Japan compared to Vietnamese and Chinese from Xishuangbana. Among these are AAC->C, ATC->G, and GAC->C (the three mutations grouped in part 1), CAC->C (the remaining type of *AC->C mutation), and ATA->A.

3. GGA->A 7mers

Since GGA->A appears to have such a strong signature of global rate variation, one might ask what the mutational profiles are for 5mers and 7mers with this 3mer subcontext.

# plot "GGA->A" type 5mers
subcontext.heatmap(norm.5mer.rates, "GGA->A", labels.5mer)

# plot "GGA->A" type 7mers
subcontext.heatmap(norm.7mer.rates, "GGA->A", labels.7mer)

This plot is less readily interpretable, since no obvious block structure emerges. The plot of 5mers suggests that CGGAG->A may be depleted in BEB, however this may just be noise (see CI plot of this mutation by ancestral population), and this signal does not appear as an evident pattern among 7mers.

Another block that may be interesting is the first group of 7mers that separates in the second clustering, which appears to be depleted in South Asia.

Overall, these plots suggest that the elevation of GGA->A is widespread among all polymorphisms with this 3mer subtype, rather than being driven by a handful of highly variable polymorphism types at the 5mer and 7mer level.

4. 3mer EAS elevation

Since experiment 1 highlighted a group of mutations (ATC->A, ACC->A, and GAC->T), which appear enriched across East Asia, it is reasonable to wonder how 5mers and 7mers with those subtypes vary.

subcontext_list.heatmap(norm.5mer.rates, c("ATC->A", "ACC->A", "GAC->T"), labels.5mer, F)

# Here I have turned off the log transformation 
# because otherwise there is very little signal to noise

This plot also does not separate into clear blocks of signals. It would appear that the signal of enrichment in East Asia is spread across nearly all 7mers with these subcontexts, except for a few which may vary due to noise. For example, the two 5mers which separate from the other contexts first have relatively noisy rate estimates owing to a small number of observations.

5. EAS heterogeneity

Since experiment 2 highlights a block of mutations elevated in Japan, we’d like to visualize how this signal fluctuates at higher context levels.

# plot these JPT-enriched 3mers at a 5mer level
norm.5mer.EAS <- norm.byrow(rates.5mer[,16:20], m = "fdiff")
subcontext_list.heatmap(norm.5mer.EAS, 
                        c("AAC->C", "ATC->G", "GAC->C", "CAC->C", "ATA->A"), labels.5mer)

This plot delineates a group of polymorphisms which appear enriched in JPT and depleted in CDX. It is not clear whether the mutation type which separates first, CGTCC->G represents a real signal - while it is depleted in KHV, the estimated rate in KHV overlaps with the CIs for all but one (CHB) of the remaining East Asian populations.

# plot JPT-enriched 3mers at a 7mer level
norm.7mer.EAS <- norm.byrow(rates.7mer[,16:20], m = "fdiff")
subcontext_list.heatmap(norm.7mer.EAS, 
                        c("AAC->C", "ATC->G", "GAC->C", "CAC->C", "ATA->A"), labels.7mer)

Among the 7mers, the first group that separates out appears similarly promising. One interesting feature is that these groups separate out not only by JPT enrichment but by CDX depletion. This makes sense based on the fact that rows are all normalized. Even if the enrichment is seen to varying degrees in CHS, CHB, and JPT, this will appear as a depletion in the population which is consistently not enriched for these mutations: CDX.

The following code is a helper method which makes a heatmap of all 7mers with a given list of 5mer subcontexts.

subcontext_list.5mers.heatmap <- function(rates, muts, labels, logunits = T){
  data <- subset(rates, labels$X5mer == muts[[1]])
  for (i in 2:length(muts)){
    data <- rbind(data, subset(rates, labels$X5mer == muts[[i]]))
  }
  rows <- apply(data, 1, function(row) all(row != 0)&all(!is.na(row)))
  return(make.heatmap(data[rows,], logunits))
}

Using the function above, we can visualize all 7mers which have 5mer contexts that fall into the first cluster in the first heatmap of this section.

# 5mers in the first separated group which appears JPT elevated
interesting.5mers <- c("CGTGC->G", "AGTCG->G", "AGACG->C", "CGATC->C", "CAACA->C", 
                       "AATAA->A", "CCACA->C", "CGTGA->G", "AGTCC->G", "AAACC->C", 
                       "TAACA->C", "ACACC->C", "CCACC->C", "CGACC->C", "CCACG->C", 
                       "TGACA->C", "CGATA->C", "GAACA->C")

# plot 7mers which have one of these 5mers as the subcontext
subcontext_list.5mers.heatmap(norm.7mer.EAS, interesting.5mers, labels.7mer)

Future directions

One analysis that would be interesting (though possibly tedious to do) is to check for the overlap between the clusters of mutations suggested by the three heatmaps in this section.

Additionally, CAAACCC->C, the very strong signature of heterogeneity in East Asia that we identified in our first analysis, is enriched on the X chromosome. Two experiments come out of this example:

  1. If we remove the X chromosome, do we see the same signal?

  2. Among the mutations that we’ve identified as interesting in this analysis, how many are X enriched? Is this more than we would expect from random chance (Binomial(n, p = 0.05))?

Weaknesses

There are a few broad weaknesses to this analysis

  1. There is no correction for uncertainty. This causes mutation types with relatively few observations (and thus, usually a high variance in rate across populations), to obscure real results.

  2. Plotting more than a couple hundred polymorphism types tends to get messy, fast. This makes it harder to make sense of patterns at higher sequence context levels (although, for the moment, it’s the best we’ve got).
